m to Berkeley to study artificial intelligence.  Berkeley 1962-3 the best year in his life so far.  Had met Isabelle but she was still in high school, so alone.  Had already learnt German, now learnt English.  Father believed you best learn a language in 
t
he bedroom.  Not many important influences from Berkeley for sociology, although did himself talk to French club on David Riesman.  Before free speech movement.  Compared with France, struck by the convenience of libraries, and more egalitarian social rel
ations.  Young people looked healthier.  Likes the practicality of the language.  Instance of a }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid11999724\charrsid4593572 self-centered}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  American widow.  Supermarkets.  Had a car.  Less easy than in France to find pretty women, and making love forbidden.
\par 
\par His friend David Castelnau f
rom Polytechnique, in next room, told Daniel about a fascinating old Trotskyite.  Tragedy of knowing the truth, but not being heard.  Sociology should be reflexive of society.  If had become a writer, would have wanted to describe society, like Balzac or 
Zola.  His own problem now is that his language is Marxese, but people don\rquote t understand that any more.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 First really encountered Marx a little later, when started sociology: through Raymond Aron.  Father was never a Marxist, strongly anti-Stalinist.  Thinks Aron never read }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Capital}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 , was interested in Marx as analyst of politics and class struggle.  Daniel read }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Capital}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  after May 1968: that was the turning point.  Gramsci not an influence (though }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Carnets de prison}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  were translated); nor Lukacs (although Lucien G
oldman a disciple).  Georges Gourvich a Russian Marxist, but with a totally personal theory.  Marx was present in the intellectual atmosphere of the 1960s, as with Sartre, but understood differently \endash 
 philosophically, rather than as relevant to the contemp
orary situation.  Father not a friend of Sartre, but Aron was very close to him, and told Sartre about recent German philosophy.  Remembers early seminar, when he did not know the meaning of potlatch, praxis, dialectic \endash 
 school teaching in philosophy had been poor.  Father did not pass on his political and philosophical knowledge.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Returned to France summer 1963.  Refused to join the programme for building a French atomic bomb.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Of his two brothers, Jean-Luc wanted to do science, astrophysics.  Playing with
 rockets as a boy.  Now one of the top astrophysicians in France.  Michel started in Science Pol, but failed after the first year, did law, and returned.  Became a lawyer with military airplane manufacturer.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Daniel had signed for 15 years.  Little choice because then dependent on father\rquote 
s financial support.  Still nine years to go.  Joined research centre at Ecole National Sup\'e9rieur d\rquote Aeronautique, still working on artificial intelligence.  Does not feel this field was significant for him in the long-term,
 but working on the huge computers at Berkeley, trying to write indexing programmes, was interesting then.  Back in France, put to work with an older engineer who did not really understand artificial intelligence, depended on Daniel, so he was able to sec
ure free Thursdays to study sociology.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 \tab 
\par Isabelle had come out to Berkeley in December 1962 to join him.  In the summer they travelled in Mexico, with Jean-Luc.  Became engaged, living together, and Isabelle became pregnant: a new couple.  She had been stud
ying Russian, and made a friend with another student Hel\'e8ne who was married to Jacques Commaille, sociologist from working class background \endash  who told Daniel how to get into sociology. So Daniel registered at the Sorbonne.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid11999724\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 At the Sorbonne took sociology, 
social psychology, demography, political economy (started to read Marx).  Loved all except sociology, taught by Raymond Aron and Gourvich, which did not satisfy him: he wanted to study real life.  After two years awarded his only degree in sociology, Lice
nce de Sociologie.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
For Isabelle, Russian was not the right choice, and she did not finish, although went on studying after their first daughter [Louise] was born.  Second daughter Sandrine born in May 1968.  Then Isabelle returned to study history, with go
od professors, especially Michelle Perrault.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978 
\par 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Isabelle\rquote s background not intellectual, her father a self-made plumber-electrician who installed central heating systems, and moved from the north to Paris.  Her father
\rquote s doubts about Daniel, but he bought them
 their first small apartment, and reconstructed it.  Story of their meeting by chance on cross-channel ferry, and re-finding her in her Montmorency suburb.  She was not yet 15.  Then lost touch when Daniel went to his military service.  How Isabelle chang
ed, spoke little but on target, wise.  Also gained from studying history, more concrete.  Women mature faster. }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Administratively, bound to the Air Force for 15 years: how to leave?
\par 
\par Won a grant from Fondation St G\'e8re Polignac to travel, intended for young 
men who would become national decision-makers.  Isolation of educated French through lack of languages.  Describes visiting the general who would present his application: being the son of Pierre Bertaux probably a disadvantage, since most of the senior of
ficers had sided with P}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\lang2057\langfe2057\langnp2057\insrsid4206422\charrsid12928687 \'e9}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
tain rather than the Resistance.  Story of the curious after-lunch Board discussion which led to his award.  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Decided to travel poor, buses and trains, but spend much on camera and films; also to go to Third World, not USA.  So went
 to East Africa, India, China, Japan, Latin America.  Meeting people, and travel trials.  In Brazil caught in a fire and nearly died.  Kept some notes, and printed a report on his experiences.  Not able, for example, to compare social systems of India and
 China, but was sensitised to Third World problems.  Began to understand imperialism from below, to see Vietnam }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4006041\charrsid4593572 War}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  differently.  Found that the French diplomats he met knew little about the countries they were working in.  Because of burns, cut end of journey (to Cuba) and returned December 1965.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Returned to job and tried to register at Sorbonne to finish Licence de Sociologie.  In October 1963, through his mother, had begun to read Oscar Lewis, decided that was what he
\rquote d like to know.  Did not know Lewis was an anthropologist, though}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4006041 t}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
 he was sociologist.  So had been very disappointed by sociology, which was Durkheim and Pareto rather than Balzac and Zola.  Thought of Lewis when in Mexico.  Registered 1966 and 1967 for political economy and demography (his mathematics helped) \endash 
 so never studied anthropology.  Political economy to reading a lot of Marx.  Completed degree summer 1967.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4006041\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Had a well-paid job, 3000 francs a month, wife and three-year-old \endash  but wanted to become a writer.  Did not know how to do it
.  Boring work by day, interesting evening talk in caf\'e9s with Commaille, friends from Qu\'e9
bec, etc.  Felt his real life was on the margins.  Then at work, had been researching on computer recognition of letters, then put onto aerial photography.  After seve
ral months realised that his work was to be used by the Americans in Vietnam.  Decided he must stop.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Applied for CNRS, with support from Raymond Aron: wrote a project on occupational choice, which he showed to (then young) Bourdieu, who was very critical.
  Wanted to compare social mobility (although did not know that term) in France, USA and Soviet Union. The Air Force agreed to release him on indefinite leave from March 1968.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Earlier, when learning to fly, much spare time because of fogs, so studied Russian.  Comparison with Russia goes back to father\rquote 
s belief that must know about both USA and Soviet Union.  He had sent Daniel on tourist trip to Russia 1958.  Liked it, found the young women more open.  At his Institute, would meet the visiting Russian res
earchers.  Went again in 1964 and also with Isabelle in 1967, travelling in the south.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Teaching methods for Masters students from start with Aron Jamus, Jewish Lebanese, had been sent by father to study jewellery but switched to social psychology, had a b
eautiful wife, one of their friendship group.  Daniel taught the mathematical methods, but by autumn 1968 teaching life history method.  The other teachers Bourdieu and Touraine.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4006041\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Started in Raymond Aron\rquote s European research centre.  Aron most interested in international relations, once told Daniel, \'93I am not a sociologist, really\'94
.  Aron told Daniel that Bourdieu would teach him, but he did not.  Bourdieu already a very charismatic guru, Daniel hoped to be called by him, but was not.  Bourdieu eventually told him that because of Daniel\rquote 
s connections (Aron, his father) and his impressive scientific qualifications, he could not teach him in the usual way as a fieldwork apprentice, interviewing, coding, observing, etc.  Too high status for this.
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\ul\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Never close to
 Bourdieu, but he conveyed that Daniel had been loyal.  Loyalty to the boss was crucial at that time.  Open war between the research centre heads: the older were Aron and Gourvich (died 1967), the younger Touraine, Bourdieu, Boudon and Michel Crozier (fro
m Science Pol, his field sociology of organisation) \endash 
 the Gang of Four.   At this time much government money put into social research, belief in need for social change, and this intensified rivalries.  Also competing for office space, for students.   Tough 
game.  Many younger people very exposed.  Bourdieu, Touraine, Boudon, expected followers to read all their work and quote only them.  Aron saw them as entrepreneurs.  But almost feudal barons, or like religious wars.  The fighting still goes on between th
eir inheritors.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid15663978\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 After his two years with Bourdieu, Daniel switched to Boudon\rquote 
s centre for three years, and since then with Touraine.  Had been working on social mobility, wrote a long mainly mathematical paper in }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Revue Fran\'e7aise de Sociologie}{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 , which Boudon
 liked, so invited him to join team 1970.  Soon clashed with Boudon of the use of a Marxist term in research application on youth movements, so Daniel withdrew.  For a whole year had been reading }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Das Kapital}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  instead of newspaper: had become a new believer.  But against Soviet system, and party leadership \endash 
 attracted initially by Maoism, was more an anarchist.  But fascinated by Marx, and remained faithful.  Bourdieu also liked Marx, had a class analysis, as did Touraine, but Boudon did not, so Daniel could not really get along with him.}{\rtlch\fcs1 
\af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
Touraine very authoritarian, big ego, Protestant work ethic.  His books loose.  But unlike the others, he had a vision of history, the dynamics of the historical situation.  Touraine\rquote s comment that union activity at CNRS fav
oured the bureaucracy rather than the research directors.  Good analyses of Chile, Poland, France.  Daniel closest to him.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Intellectually closer to Bourdieu, but Bourdieu hostile because Daniel failed to quote him enough.  Disapproves very much of Bourdieu\rquote 
s practice of only quoting friends, never quoting enemies.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Story of Boudon, after a year, asking Daniel to leave his centre, because did not fit into its orientation.  But did not go for two years, until Touraine could accept him. }{
\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
May 1968 a revelation, because had not been previously reading Marx.  Came back from two-month visit to Russia, contacting Soviet sociologists, to find France in turmoil, his students in turmoil.  Sandrine born 25 May.  Visited occupied Sorbonne, found th
e debates boring.  Set up liaison committee to help striking workers, to bu}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid5900228 y}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
 food, etc.  Avoided street fighting.  Politically, incredibly rich.  Suddenly the French working class was again there, with a space to express themselves.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Destins personnels et structures de classe}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
 written after an interval, 1976.  But teaching life stories from autumn 1968.  Inspiration from Oscar Lewis and from}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid5900228  C.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  Wright Mills\rquote  }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Sociological Imagination}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 
: that research should focus on the intersection of history and social structure in biography.  Mills had also written }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Character and Social Structure}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572  with Hans Gerdt.  Daniel took from Bourdieu (and Durkheim) the view that sociology is not psychology \endash  psychological states the internalisation of experience (Sa
rtre, the internalising of what is outside).  And the idea of }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \i\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 habitus}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid5900228  (from}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Simmel).  Wishes he knew more about psychology, but }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid5900228 psychoanalysis expensive, canno}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 
\f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 t read Freud in German, and found Lacan incomprehensible.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 For a long time, saw no possible connec
tion between studying social mobility and life stories.  So started with survey work (influencing Boudon), met Otis Dudley Duncan and other Americans.  Most work is on mathematical models.  Log-linear model taken up by Goldthorpe.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 
\ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Social mobility research
 led very early to the idea of anthroponomy.  Catastrophic lack of theory in the field.    Social mobility perceived differently in different cultures.  Should be part of general sociology: seen as part of structure, rather than as individual competition.
  Extending Marx\rquote 
s production of goods to the production and people, making babies into socialised human beings, and their distribution and consumption by society: the consumption of human energy and skills.  Calls this anthroponomy.  The idea of the double
 process of production of things and people is in Marx and Engels, but they did not develop it, except in relation to primitive societies.  Thinks that even in industrialised society, the production of people is the most crucial.
\par 
\par Health, education are part of the process of producing or transforming human beings.  Also housework; catering, hotels\rquote  leisure services.  This is the theory for which he would like to be recognised \endash 
 but nobody takes it seriously: his life drama.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid8261760\charrsid4593572 
\par }{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572\charrsid4593572 Not good at the academic power g
ame, which Bourdieu and earlier Durkheim played; and came at the wrong time, after the spoils had been divided by the Gang of Four.  To start your own team, you need political allies in government, office space, old boy network of support.  Does not have 
these supports.}{\rtlch\fcs1 \af0\afs22 \ltrch\fcs0 \f40\fs22\insrsid4593572 
